Date:6/10/2004 12:47:54 PM
From:Sam Citron
How valuable is value?
By Mark Hulbert, CBS.MarketWatch.com

[I thought there were some other valuable points such as how different
measurements of value compared, so I have reproduced the entire article]

Not all value stocks are created equal.

I realize that this hardly is earth-shattering news. Yet investors don't always
act as though they believe it. Instead, they treat "value" as though it refers
to a monolithic group of stocks.

Consider, for example, how mutual funds are evaluated. Managers are judged
according to how well they have done relative to their benchmarks, and when it
comes to value funds, funds that employ widely different definitions of value
nevertheless are compared to the same benchmark.

To see how little sense that makes, we need a few definitions.

Most academics define value using the price-to-book ratio: Stocks whose ratios
are low are considered to be value stocks, while those with high price-to-book
ratios are considered to be in the growth category.

Other widely used definitions focus on the price-to-earnings ratio, the
price-to-cash flow ratio, the price-to-sales ratio, and so forth. In all cases,
value stocks are those with the lowest ratios and growth stocks are those with
the highest.

Unfortunately, however, these various definitions don't always agree on which
stocks are value and which ones are growth. That is, a stock with a low P/E
ratio may nevertheless have a high price/book ratio, or vice versa.

How have these various definitions performed over the past decade? Richard
Moroney provided an answer in the May issue of his newsletter, Upside. (Moroney
also edits Dow Theory Forecasts.)

Moroney arrived at his answer by back-testing the performance of a number of
hypothetical portfolios that differed according to which definitions of value
that they used. He measured these portfolios' performances from 1992 until
earlier this year.

The table below lists the four definitions of value that performed the best
over this period. In each case, the percentage reflects the average annual
extent to which the 20 percent of stocks that most satisfied the definition
outperformed the overall market.

Definition of value Average annual lead over market
Price/free cash flow 9.1 percent
Price/sales vs. 5-year median 8.1 percent
Price/earnings 7.4 percent
Price/sales 7.1 percent

Moroney stresses that these are back tests, and that he is "skeptical an
investor could have done as well as the best test suggests." He also points out
that these tests focused on holding periods of no longer than a year, and that
if they had focused on longer holding periods, other ratios would have come out
on top.

Nevertheless, as you can see from the table, the best performer was the
definition based on the ratio of price to free cash flow -- which refers to
cash generated by a company's operations, less capital spending and dividends.

Taking this result to heart, I decided to screen for stocks that have very
attractive price/free cash-flow ratios and which are also popular among
investment newsletters. I started by using a stock-ranking system maintained by
Moroney at his Web site, known as the Quadrix system.

That system places all stocks on a 0-to-100 scale according to their ratios of
price/free cash flow, with 100 representing most value and 0 representing least
value.

The table that follows shows those stocks that earned a grade of 75 or higher
on Moroney's ranking system and which also are currently recommended for
purchase by five or more newsletters on the Hulbert Financial Digest's
monitored list:

Ticker Company No. of newsletters recommending
CFC Countrywide Financial 9
VZ Verizon 8
COP ConocoPhillips 8
CVX ChevronTexaco 8
ECA Encana 7
NXTL Nextel 7
AT Alltell 5
VLO Valero 5
JPM JP Morgan Chase 5
ADM Archer Daniel Midland 5
