From:Sam Citron
Let's apply Mark Hulbert's Price/Free Cash Flow holy grail to Countrywide
[CFC]. True their FCF (free cash flow) is just amazing. According to Yahoo:

Mkt Cap: 19.04B
FCF: 7.26B
P/FCF: 2.62
Operating Margin: 50.56%
http://finance.yahoo.com/q/ks?s=cfc

These numbers look almost too good to be true. And perhaps they are. For one
thing, Value Line lists their "Cash Flow per Share" at only $8.45, versus
$27.09 for Yahoo [Cash flow from operations: $7.57B/279.38M shares]. So I don't
know which cash flow numbers to believe, Yahoos or Value Line's.

Then there's the question of whether this is as good as it possibly gets for a
residential mortgage lender with rates now headed in a northerly direction.
Already CFC has noted some disturbing trends in their May operational report,
although they tried to place the best possible spin on them:

Average daily application volume of $2 billion declined 39 percent from last
year amidst a higher interest rate environment.

Applications fell "only" 5 percent as compared to last month. [!]

Pipeline of applications-in-process at $50 billion, down from the year-ago
period when it was $74 billion.

Loan fundings for the month of May totaled $32 billion, a decrease of 20
percent from last year.

And last but not least, declining quality of their loan portfolio with subprime
volume surpassing $3 billion, an increase of 89 percent over last year.

At the risk of differing with nonagenarian Seth Glickenhouse's bullish
assessment in this week's Barrons ["Buying Countrywide is like buying the
Michael Jordan of the industry at a preposterously low price: eight times this
year's earnings."
http://online.wsj.com/barrons/article/0,,SB108639081396029410,00.html?mod=b_thi
_weeks_magazine_main ], I'll forego this bargain awaiting further research,
such as how well they actually perform in a rising rate environment, which we
have not seen in a good long time.
